First, let's map the primary variables of interest, year and military expenditure, to the ggplot function.

In [63]:
ggplot(plotdata, aes(x = year, y = milex))

Now, let's add the relevant points using geom_point().

In [61]:
ggplot(plotdata, aes(x = year, y = milex)) + geom_point()

Next, let's make the size of the data points correspond with the military personnel of a great power country in a given year.

In [60]:
ggplot(plotdata, aes(x = year, y = milex, size = milper)) + geom_point()

Following this, let's differentiate between the great power countries by color coding them using their state abbreviations.

In [59]:
ggplot(plotdata, aes(x = year, y = milex, size = milper, color = stateabb)) + 
    geom_point()

Finally, let's add the necessary axis labels, legend labels, and plot title to help the interpretability of the plot. We've also added a "light" theme as well.

In [69]:
ggplot(plotdata, aes(x = year, y = milex, size = milper, color = stateabb)) +
    geom_point() + labs(x = "Year", y = "Military Expenditure", 
       title = "Military Personnel and Expenditures by Year among Great Powers", size = "Military Personnel",
       color = "State") + theme_light()
